Boolean Logic

  • AND, OR, NOT, XOR, \(\to\), \(\iff\)
A B A \(\land\) B A \(\to\) B A \(\iff\) B
F F F T T
F T F T F
T F F F F
T T T T T
  • When two functions are different it means their outputs are different
    • i.e. AND should have at least one output different than OR
  • For A \(\iff\) B, when A is F and B is T, read from right to left. When A is T and B is F, read from left to right
    • i.e. start reading with the one that is false
  • A \(\subseteq\) B: \(\forall\) x, if x \(\in\) A then x \(\in\) B
  • 16 functions of 2 boolean varialbes (\(2^4\), you have four combinations of 2)
    • 4 rows of the truth table and 2 options for each row
  • How many boolean functions do we have on n boolean variables?
    • \(2^{2^{n}}\)

Distributive Laws

  • a(b + c) = (a + b)(a + c)
  • P \(\land\) (Q \(\lor\) R) = (P \(\land\) Q) \(\lor\) (P \(\land\) R)
  • P \(\lor\) (A \(\land\) R) = (P \(\lor\) Q) \(\land\) (P \(\lor\) R)

Regular Languages

  • As characters are read, they start following arrows into different states

State Diagram

  • Example Strings:
    • 00001 \(\to\) accepted
    • 1001 \(\to\) accepted
    • 0 \(\to\) rejected
    • \(\lambda \to\) rejected
    • \(\lambda\) is the empty string

Finite Automaton

  • Specified by a 5-tuple
    • \(Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_o, F\)
      • \(Q\) = finite set of states
      • \(\Sigma\) = finite alphabet
      • \(\delta\) = \(Q \times \Sigma \to Q\) (transition function)
      • \(q_o\) = starting state
      • \(F\) = set of accepting states
    • The language of \(M\) is \(L(M) = A\) and that is the set of all strings accepted by \(M\)
    • We can also say that \(M\) recognizes \(A\) or \(M\) accepts \(A\)
    • In our example…
      • \(W\) ends with a 1, ends with an even number of 0s provided that you have at least one 1.
    • Language \(A=\left\{w \in \left\{0, 1\right\}^{*} |w~has~an~even~number~of~0s\right\}\)
      • the * after \(\left\{0, 1\right\}\) means that you can concatenate as many functions (characters? I can’t remember) as you want

      • Two states, expressing the parity of 0s

        State Diagram

  • Represented as a 5-tuple
    • \(\left(\left\{q_{even}, q_{odd}, \left\{0, 1\right\}, \delta, q_{even}, \left\{q_{odd}\right\}\right\}\right)\) where delta is:

\(q_{even}\) 0 \(q_{odd}\)

\(q_{even}\) 0 \(q_{odd}\)
\(q_{odd}\) 1 \(q_{even}\)

\(q_{even}\) \(q_{odd}\) \(q_{even}\)

  • Language \(B=\left\{w | w~ends~in~a~1~or~w=\lambda\right\}\)

  • Language \(C=\left\{w|w~starts~with~and~ends~with~a~0~or~starts~with~and~ends~with~a~1\right\}\)

Computation

  • Formal definition: Let \(M=(Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_o, F)\) be a finite automaton. Let \(w = w_1,w_2,...,w_n\) be a string where each \(w_i\) is a member of \(\Sigma\). Then \(M\) accepts \(w\) if there is a sequence of states \(r_o, r_1, r_2,...,r_n\) in \(Q\) such that:
    • \(r_o = q_o\)
    • $r_{i+1} = (r_i, w_{i+1}) for \(i \in\) {0,1,2,…,n-1}
    • \(r_n \in F\)

Regular Languages

  • A language is called regular if there is some automaton that recognizes it

Regular Operators

  • Let \(A\) and \(B\) be languages. We define the regular operators \(\cup\), \(\circ\), \(*\) as follows:
    • \(\cup\): A \(\cup\) B = \(\left\{w~|~w \in A \lor w \in B\right\}\)
    • \(\circ\): A \(\circ\) B = \(\left\{w=xy~|~x \in A \land y \in B\right\}\)
    • \(*\): A\(*\) = \(\left\{w_1, w_2,...,w_k~|~w_i \in A \land k \geq 0\right\}\)

Theorem

  • The class of regular languages is closed under the \(\cup\) operation. In other words, if \(A_1\) and \(A_2\) are regular languages, then so is \(A_1 \cup A_2\)
